04629nam a22006135i 9781474472784DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222001stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744727847 a10.1515/97814744727842doi  a(DE-B1597)615443  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0190002bisacsh1 aSperling, Liz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWomen, Political Philosophy and Politics /cLiz Sperling. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tChapter 1: Women, Political Philosophy and Politics: Theory and Practice in Conflict? -- tChapter 2: The State of Nature and the Origins of the Exclusionary State -- tChapter 3: The State that Ends at the Front Door -- tChapter 4: Citizenship and Representation: A Case of Protective Custody? -- tChapter 5: Plato and Aristotle: Androcracy Incarnate -- tChapter 6: Hobbes and Locke: Divine Right of Contract Man -- tChapter 7: Rousseau: Education for the Common Good -- tChapter 8: Mill, Marx and Engels: Equality and the Common Man -- tChapter 9: Rawls and Nozick: Justice and Masculinised Politics -- tChapter 10: Never Decreasing Circles: The Legacy of Political Philosophy -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis new book explores the interface between political philosophy and politics, looking at the effects of philosophical traditions on the contemporary relationship between women and politics.Analysing key concepts in political philosophy, the author illustrates how common ideas - entrenched in the development of political thought and practice - have become almost intractable 'truths' that continue to differentiate between the sexes in politics.Liz Sperling looks in detail at the works of Plato, Aristotle, Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau, Mill, Marx, Rawls and Nozick, considering general themes to which they have all contributed - such as the state of nature, the state, markets, citizenship and representation. The focus then turns to the specific contributions of the philosophers that continue to influence the association of women to politics. These include an analysis of Greek classicists' establishment of andocracy, Rousseau's treatise on education for citizenship, and nineteenth-century ideas of equality.In conclusion, the themes demonstrated throughout are drawn together to show how they translate into contemporary policy on women in politics. Offering an original insight into the ways in which political thought influences political practice, this will be essential reading in a key area of politics, philosophy and women's studies.Key FeaturesExplores the interface between political philosophy and practical politicsCovers key political philosophers over time - Plato, Aristotle, Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau, Mill, Marx, Rawls, NozickUniquely examines the effects of traditional philosophy on the contemporary relationship between women and politics  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aPolitics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447278440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474472784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474472784/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aP